So I&#x27;m trying to use an image from my Google Container Registry, since this is a private registry I need to [authenticate|https://cloud.google.com/container-registry/docs/advanced-authentication].

Obviously I don&#x27;t want to renew my auth token every hour to make my pipelines work, so I need to go for the json key file.

It works when I define the image as follows:

{code}
#!yaml
image:
   name: eu.gcr.io/project_id/image:latest
   username: _json_key
   password: >
      {JSON file content}
   email: pipelines@bitbucket.com
{code}

But that means your json key file is out in the open available for everyone with access to the pipelines fine to see, not what I&#x27;d like.

Then I&#x27;ve put the contents of the JSON file into an Environment Variable and replaced the actual json with the environment variable as follows:

{code}
#!yaml
image:
   name: eu.gcr.io/project_id/image:latest
   username: _json_key
   password: >
      ${JSON_KEY}
   email: pipelines@bitbucket.com
{code}

Somehow in the second scenario it doesn&#x27;t work :(

I tried the multiple ways [described|https://confluence.atlassian.com/bitbucket/deploy-build-outputs-to-bitbucket-downloads-872124574.html] in documentation and in issues to use curl to upload build artifacts do repository Downloads.

The only syntax I have found to work is this:

{code}
#!yaml

curl -X POST --user "${BITBUCKET_REPO_OWNER}:${BB_AUTH_STRING}" "https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/${BITBUCKET_REPO_OWNER}/${BITBUCKET_REPO_SLUG}/downloads/" --form files=@"bin/slug"
{code}

That is, this does not work (no password part):

{code}
#!yaml

curl -X POST --user "${BB_AUTH_STRING}" "https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/${BITBUCKET_REPO_OWNER}/${BITBUCKET_REPO_SLUG}/downloads/" --form files=@"bin/slug"
{code}

This doesn&#x27;t work:

{code}
#!yaml

curl -X POST "${BB_AUTH_STRING}@https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/${BITBUCKET_REPO_OWNER}/${BITBUCKET_REPO_SLUG}/downloads/" --form files=@"bin/slug"
{code}

The later versions APPEAR to work, the curl upload succeeds, but no files are available in "Downloads" and the access time of the app password is NOT updated.

Currently Bitbucket often produces messy diffs, like:

{code}
     private void modifiedMethod(final List<Foo> foos) {
         for (final Foo foo : foos) {
+            boolean frobbled = service.frobble(foo);
+            if (frobbled) {
+                doSomethingMore();
+            }
+        }
+    }
+
+    /**
+     * @return Something completely unrelated
+     */
+    static String addedMethod() {
+        return "asdf";
+    }
+
+    /**
+     * Long
+     * Javadoc
+     *
+     * Is
+     * Long
+     *
+     * Lorem ipsum etc.
+     *
+     * @param myParam
+     *         I take a parameter
+     */
+    private void anotherNewMethod(Integer parameter) {
+        if (parameter != null) {
+            return parameter + 1;
         }
     }
{code}

Git nowadays has patience diff algorithm, which should produce nicer diffs with less conflation between methods at least curly-braced languages, along the lines of:

{code}
